1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,500
So I've been testing this new AI coding tool for the past two weeks

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:08,200
and honestly, it completely changed how I write code.

3
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:12,800
Before I get into the results, let me give you some context.

4
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:17,500
I'm a full-stack developer, been coding for about seven years now.

5
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:22,000
I mainly work with React and Node, some Python on the side.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,300
So when I first heard about this tool, I was skeptical.

7
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:30,500
Like, really skeptical. I've tried a bunch of AI tools before.

8
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:34,800
Most of them just generate boilerplate that you end up rewriting anyway.

9
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:39,200
But this one was different. Let me show you what happened.

10
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:44,500
Day one, I gave it a pretty complex task. Build a REST API with authentication.

11
00:00:44,500 --> 00:00:49,000
JWT tokens, role-based access, the whole thing.

12
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,500
And it just... did it. Like, correctly. First try.

13
00:00:53,500 --> 00:00:58,200
Not just boilerplate. Actual production-quality code with error handling.

14
00:00:58,200 --> 00:01:03,000
I spent the next hour just reading through the code, checking for issues.

15
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,500
Found maybe two minor things I wanted to change. Two. In an entire API.

16
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:12,000
That would have taken me at least a full day to write from scratch.

17
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,500
By day three, I was using it for everything.

18
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:21,000
Refactoring old code, writing tests, even debugging.

19
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,500
The debugging part actually blew my mind.

20
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:30,000
I had this bug that I'd been stuck on for three days.

21
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:34,500
Three days of console.log debugging, reading Stack Overflow.

22
00:01:34,500 --> 00:01:39,000
I pasted the error and the relevant code, and it found the issue in like ten seconds.

23
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:43,500
It was a race condition in my async middleware chain.

24
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:48,000
Something I probably never would have found on my own.

25
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,500
Now here's the thing that actually surprised me the most.

26
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:57,000
After two weeks, my code quality actually got better.

27
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,500
Not because the AI wrote better code than me.

28
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:06,000
But because I started learning from the patterns it used.

29
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,500
Things like proper error boundaries, more consistent naming.

30
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:15,000
Stuff I knew I should do but was always too lazy to implement.

31
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,500
So if you're a developer and you haven't tried these tools yet,

32
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:24,000
I'd say give it two weeks. Not two days. Two weeks.

33
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,500
Because the first few days you'll fight with it.

34
00:02:28,500 --> 00:02:33,000
But once you learn how to prompt it correctly, it's a game changer.

35
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:37,500
Let me know in the comments if you want me to do a deep dive

36
00:02:37,500 --> 00:02:42,000
on exactly how I set it up and the specific prompts I use.

37
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,500
Drop a like if this was helpful. See you in the next one.
